WEEK 3 – LAB ACTION PLAN (Collaborative Coding, Conflicts & Patch)
1. Creating an Organization (GitHub)
Step 1: Go to GitHub → New Organization → Create a free organization.
Step 2: Enter organization details → Next.
Step 3: Add members → they accept the invite.
Step 4: Set access permissions:
    Settings → Member privileges → Base permissions → Write
    Projects base permissions → Write
Step 5: Create repository inside organization (private recommended).
2. Sharing Repository with Collaborators
Steps for Collaborator 1:
- Go to repository → Settings → Collaborators
- Add people → Collaborator 2 accepts the invitation

Steps for Collaborator 2 (Git commands):
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email you@example.com
git remote -v
git clone https://github.com/username/repository-name.git
cd repository-name
git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
git add .
git commit -m "Add descriptive commit message"
git push origin feature/your-feature-name

Keeping branch updated:
git checkout main
git pull origin main
git checkout feature/your-new-feature
git merge main
3. Forking and Pull Requests
1. Visit public repo (Person1).
2. Click Fork → repo copies to Person2.
3. Clone the fork:
   git clone https://github.com/your-username/awesome-project
4. Make changes:
   git add .
   git commit
   git push origin main
5. Create Pull Request → Person1 reviews → Merge Pull Request
4. Resolving Merge Conflicts
Step 1: Check conflicts
git status

Step 2: Open conflicted file (shows <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>> markers)

Step 3: Edit manually (choose/merge both versions) and remove markers.

Step 4:
git add filename.txt

Step 5:
git commit
(Or: git rebase --continue)

To cancel merge:
git merge --abort
5. Creating and Applying Patches
1. Clone any public repo.
2. Edit file → git add → git commit.
3. View commit hash:
git log
4. Create patch:
git format-patch -1 <commit-hash>
(Produces: 0001-commit-message.patch)
5. Send patch to owner.

Owner applies patch:
git apply my-changes.patch
OR (for format-patch files):
git am 0001-commit-message.patch



##commands
git --version	Check installed Git version
git config --global user.name "Your Name"	Set your global Git username
git config --global user.email "email@example.com"	Set your global Git email
git config --list	View current Git configurations
git init	Create/initialize a new Git repository
git clone <repo-url>	Copy a remote repo to local system
git remote -v	Show connected remote repositories
git remote add origin <repo-url>	Link a remote repo to local workspace
git remote remove <name>	Remove remote URL mapping
git remote rename <old> <new>	Rename a remote
git remote set-url origin <new-url>	Update remote repository URL
git remote show origin	View detailed info of remote
git add <filename>	Stage a file for commit
git add .	Stage all modified files
git reset <filename>	Remove file from staging (keep changes)
git restore --staged <file>	Unstage file with restore command
git restore <file>	Discard local (unstaged) changes
git checkout -- <file>	Old method for discarding file changes
git add <filename>	Stage a file for commit
git add .	Stage all modified files
git reset <filename>	Remove file from staging (keep changes)
git restore --staged <file>	Unstage file with restore command
git restore <file>	Discard local (unstaged) changes
git checkout -- <file>	Old method for discarding file changes
git status	View changed, staged, untracked files
git log	Show commit history
git log --oneline --graph --decorate	Visual commit history
git diff	View unstaged changes difference
git blame <file>	Show who modified each line
git branch	List local branches
git branch -a	List all local + remote branches
git branch <branch-name>	Create new branch
git checkout <branch-name>	Switch branches (old way)
git checkout -b <new-branch>	Create and switch to a new branch
git switch <branch-name>	Switch to a branch (new way)
git switch -c <branch-name>	Create & switch (new method)
git branch -d <branch-name>	Delete only if merged (safe)
git branch -D <branch-name>	Force delete even if not merged
git branch -d <branch-name>	Delete only if merged (safe)
git branch -D <branch-name>	Force delete even if not merged
git fetch origin	Download latest remote updates (no merge)
git fetch --prune	Remove deleted remote branch references
git pull origin <branch>	Fetch + merge latest changes
git push origin <branch>	Upload commits to remote branch
git push -u origin <branch>	First-time push and set tracking
git add <file>	Mark conflict resolved
git commit	Complete merge after resolution
git stash	Save changes without committing
git stash pop	Restore and delete from stash list
git stash apply	Restore but keep in stash
git reflog	View history of actions (lost commits recovery)
git checkout <commit-id>	Restore a previous commit or branch
git pull --rebase origin <branch>
Update branch while keeping linear history
